    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.27b.64"/>
                
                <note type="curatorial">Neihardt Collection
                    98</note>
                
                <fw type="curatorial">64</fw>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline>
                        3 Landseer Close
                        off Carr Road.
                        <hi rend="caps">BURNLEY.</hi>
                        Lancashire.
                        September 23rd, 1959
                    </dateline>
                    
                    <salute>Dear Sir,</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>Very seldom have I ever written to any author in this way, but I feel I must express my appreciation of your book "Eagle Voice".</p>
                
                <p>It has the rare quality of being both delightfu<unclear>lly</unclear> readable and yet instructive. At University, though my "officia<unclear>l"</unclear> study was English, I spent a lot of spare time among the books and papers &#8212; particularly Bureau of American Ethnology publications &#8212; <unclear/> in the Anthropology section of the library, and though I am not pretending to great knowledge on that account I think I have at least enough to see that your book is far above the level of ordinary fiction in its authenticity and attention to detail.</p>
                
                <p>You have described the ordinary, activities of the Sioux &#8212; their ceremonials, camp routne and particularly their humour &#8212; in a fascinating way that might seem impossible to those who seem only to think of them as an all-male nation living only for the warpath. Especially well have you tackled the difficult task of transcribing the direct speech of the Indians.</p>
                
                <p>Without sentimentality, you have presented a clear picture of the old Sioux life, whose passing I can never think of without a certain deep regret.</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>Yours faithfully,</salute>
                    <signed>K.G. Spenar.</signed>
                </closer>
                
                <note place="right margin">To open cut here &#8594;</note>
                
            </div1>
